 {"id":"franken_numpy-azql","title":"Cross-engine performance benchmark suite vs legacy NumPy","description":"## Why this exists\n\nFrankenNumPy's entire value proposition is \"drop-in NumPy replacement with rigorous architecture.\" The G7 performance budget gate (run_performance_budget_gate.sh) currently measures FrankenNumPy against a self-baseline (artifacts/baselines/ufunc_benchmark_baseline.json) — it catches *regressions* but says nothing about how we compare to actual NumPy on identical workloads. A 2026-04-09 reality check found ZERO cross-engine timing comparisons anywhere in the repo: no `numpy_time`, `vs_numpy`, `speedup`, or `ratio` identifiers exist in fnp-conformance. This is a strategic blind spot for a project whose README touts a ~56% reduction in axis-reduction latency without ever stating what we're slower or faster than.\n\n## Background / context for future-self\n\n- The conformance harness already runs real upstream NumPy via `capture_numpy_oracle` (FNP_REQUIRE_REAL_NUMPY_ORACLE=1, .venv-numpy314 bootstrap via uv). That same interpreter can time NumPy calls.\n- The README Performance section (L921) and Limitations section (L941, \"No BLAS/LAPACK backend... competitive with BLAS for small matrices; slower for large ones\") makes implicit performance claims that have never been measured against a reference.\n- Existing baseline JSON (artifacts/baselines/ufunc_benchmark_baseline.json) only tracks p50/p95/p99 of FrankenNumPy itself. Recent commit 27f27f2 added memory/allocation/fragmentation SLOs to G7 — that work should be extended, not duplicated.\n- This is NOT a request to make FrankenNumPy faster than NumPy. It's a request to MEASURE the gap honestly so we know where parity-debt grinding ends and optimization work begins.\n\n## Goals\n\n1. Define a sentinel workload set (~30-50 ops) organized by op-family AND array size tier:\n   - **Size tiers:** small (100 elements), medium (10K elements), large (1M elements). Each workload must specify which tier(s) it targets — a matmul on 2x2 vs 1000x1000 is a fundamentally different measurement.\n   - **Op-families to cover:** elementwise (add/mul/div on contiguous f64, i64, Complex128), broadcasted ops (size-1 dims, mixed-rank), axis reductions (sum/mean/std/argmax on contiguous + strided), sort + percentile, matmul (small 2x2-10x10, medium 100x100, large 1000x1000), linalg (solve, svd, eig — small + medium only), fft (power-of-2 + non-power-of-2), RNG (standard_normal, binomial, poisson — large sample sizes), IO (npy roundtrip, genfromtxt parsing).\n   - **Minimum:** 30 workloads spanning all families. Target: 40-50 for good coverage.\n\n2. For each workload, capture timing statistics for BOTH FrankenNumPy and NumPy from identical input data:\n   - **Sample protocol:** 5 warmup iterations (discarded) + 50 timed iterations (collected). Minimum 50 samples per workload to get meaningful percentiles.\n   - **Timing stats captured:** p50, p95, p99, mean, stddev, min, max, sample_count.\n   - **FrankenNumPy** runs in-process (Rust).\n   - **NumPy** runs in a SEPARATE process via FNP_ORACLE_PYTHON to isolate GIL/import-time noise. One subprocess invocation per workload (amortize Python startup across the 50 samples within that invocation).\n\n3. **Data interchange format:** Input fixtures are serialized as .npy files via fnp-io's existing npy writer. The Python harness loads them with `numpy.load()`. This validates our NPY format compatibility AS A SIDE EFFECT.\n\n4. **BLAS normalization policy:** Measure against REAL numpy-with-default-BLAS (OpenBLAS on Linux, Accelerate on macOS). This shows the gap users would actually see. The report MUST note the BLAS backend detected (`numpy.show_config()` output captured and stored in env_fingerprint). A future follow-up can add a no-BLAS baseline, but the honest first measurement uses what users actually have.\n\n5. Emit a single artifact `artifacts/baselines/cross_engine_benchmark_v1.json` with schema:\n   ```json\n   {\n     \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n     \"generated_at\": \"ISO-8601\",\n     \"git_sha\": \"abc123\",\n     \"env_fingerprint\": { \"rust_version\": \"...\", \"numpy_version\": \"...\", \"blas_backend\": \"...\", \"cpu\": \"...\", \"os\": \"...\" },\n     \"workloads\": [\n       {\n         \"family\": \"ufunc-elementwise\",\n         \"name\": \"add_f64_contiguous\",\n         \"size_tier\": \"medium\",\n         \"element_count\": 10000,\n         \"warmup\": 5,\n         \"samples\": 50,\n         \"fnp\": { \"p50_ns\": ..., \"p95_ns\": ..., \"p99_ns\": ..., \"mean_ns\": ..., \"stddev_ns\": ..., \"min_ns\": ..., \"max_ns\": ... },\n         \"numpy\": { \"p50_ns\": ..., \"p95_ns\": ..., \"p99_ns\": ..., \"mean_ns\": ..., \"stddev_ns\": ..., \"min_ns\": ..., \"max_ns\": ... },\n         \"ratio\": 5.2,\n         \"ratio_direction\": \"fnp_p50 / numpy_p50 (>1 means FNP is slower)\"\n       }\n     ]\n   }\n   ```\n   - **Ratio direction:** `fnp_p50 / numpy_p50` so ratio > 1 means FrankenNumPy is SLOWER than NumPy. This is the natural direction for identifying gaps to close. Green: ratio <= 2x. Yellow: 2x-10x. Red: >10x.\n\n6. RaptorQ-protect the artifact (sidecar + scrub_report + decode_proof) to match the durability discipline used everywhere else.\n\n7. Add `scripts/e2e/run_cross_engine_benchmark.sh` that drives the bin and validates the artifact. The script must:\n   - Bootstrap .venv-numpy314 if not present (reuse existing oracle bootstrap logic).\n   - Run the benchmark bin with `FNP_REQUIRE_REAL_NUMPY_ORACLE=1`.\n   - Validate the output JSON schema (required fields present, all workloads have both fnp and numpy timings).\n   - Validate RaptorQ sidecar integrity.\n   - Print a summary table to stdout (pass/fail + ratio highlights).\n   - Exit 0 on success, non-zero on schema or integrity failure.\n\n8. Generate a markdown summary report (`artifacts/baselines/cross_engine_benchmark_v1.report.md`) with:\n   - One row per workload, grouped by op-family.\n   - Columns: workload name, size tier, FNP p50, NumPy p50, ratio, band (green/yellow/red).\n   - Summary statistics at top: total workloads, median ratio, worst ratio, best ratio, count per band.\n   - BLAS backend noted prominently.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- Do NOT gate CI on absolute performance vs NumPy yet — too much variance across workers, and we'd be locking in current numbers as \"acceptable.\" This bead delivers MEASUREMENT only.\n- Do NOT optimize FrankenNumPy in this bead. Optimization is a separate bead family (franken_numpy-w4zs) that depends on this one.\n- Do NOT include workloads that are explicitly disclaimed (multi-threaded ops, BLAS-backed linalg on huge matrices) — those are tracked separately.\n- Do NOT try to \"fix\" poor ratios — just measure and report honestly.\n\n## Implementation sketch\n\n1. New file `crates/fnp-conformance/src/cross_engine_benchmark.rs` defining:\n   - `WorkloadSpec` struct (family: String, name: String, size_tier: String, element_count: usize, op: String, warmup: usize, samples: usize).\n   - `WorkloadResult` struct (spec + fnp_timings + numpy_timings + ratio + ratio_direction).\n   - `CrossEngineBenchmarkReport` struct (version, git_sha, env_fingerprint, workloads: Vec<WorkloadResult>).\n   - `fn run_cross_engine_benchmark(repo_root, manifest_path, oracle_python) -> Result<Report>`.\n   - `fn generate_markdown_report(report) -> String`.\n   - `fn compute_percentiles(samples: &[u64]) -> TimingStats` — sorts and indexes, handles small-sample edge cases.\n\n2. Python timing harness as an embedded string template (or a file under `scripts/benchmarks/numpy_timer.py`). The harness:\n   - Accepts CLI args: `--workload-json <path>` containing op name, input .npy path, warmup, samples.\n   - Loads input with `numpy.load()`, runs the op in a tight loop, captures `time.perf_counter_ns()` per iteration.\n   - Writes timings JSON to stdout. Errors to stderr.\n   - MUST import numpy only once and reuse across iterations (but NOT across workloads — one subprocess per workload for isolation).\n\n3. Rust side generates the .npy fixture for each workload via fnp-io, writes it to a tempdir, invokes the Python subprocess, reads back the timing JSON, runs the same op in FrankenNumPy in-process with the same warmup/samples protocol, computes ratios.\n\n4. Sentinel workloads defined in `artifacts/contracts/cross_engine_benchmark_workloads_v1.yaml` so the set is reviewable and versioned. Each entry specifies: family, name, op, dtype, shape, size_tier, warmup, samples, and any op-specific parameters (e.g., axis for reductions, bandwidth for fft).\n\n5. New bin `crates/fnp-conformance/src/bin/run_cross_engine_benchmark.rs` matching the existing pattern (parse args, call library function, exit with status).\n\n6. Wire RaptorQ via the existing `raptorq_artifacts` module — same pattern as conformance_bundle_v1 and benchmark_bundle_v1.\n\n## Unit test requirements\n\nTests MUST be inline `#[cfg(test)]` in `cross_engine_benchmark.rs`:\n\n1. **Workload manifest parsing:** Load the YAML manifest, verify all required fields present, verify schema validation rejects missing fields.\n2. **Percentile computation:** Test `compute_percentiles` with known data (10 samples: [1,2,...,10], verify p50=5, p95=10, p99=10). Test with single sample. Test with empty input returns error.\n3. **Ratio computation:** Verify ratio = fnp_p50 / numpy_p50. Verify ratio direction string. Verify band assignment: ratio=1.5 -> green, ratio=5.0 -> yellow, ratio=15.0 -> red. Test edge case: numpy_p50 = 0 (division guard).\n4. **Report JSON schema round-trip:** Serialize a `CrossEngineBenchmarkReport`, deserialize, compare. Verify all fields survive round-trip.\n5. **Markdown report generation:** Generate from a known report, verify it contains expected headers, all workloads appear, summary stats are correct.\n6. **Environment fingerprint capture:** Verify `env_fingerprint` includes rust_version, numpy_version, cpu, os fields.\n7. **NPY fixture generation:** Verify that writing a test array to .npy and reading it back produces identical data (exercises fnp-io round-trip as a side-effect).\n\n## E2E test requirements\n\n`scripts/e2e/run_cross_engine_benchmark.sh` must:\n- Run the full benchmark with a REDUCED workload set (3-5 workloads, 3 warmup, 5 samples) for speed in CI.\n- Validate output JSON exists and has correct schema.\n- Validate RaptorQ sidecar + scrub_report + decode_proof exist and pass integrity checks.\n- Validate markdown report exists and is non-empty.\n- Log detailed progress to stderr (which workload is running, FNP timing, NumPy timing, ratio) so debugging is possible.\n- Support `--quick` flag for CI (reduced workloads) vs full run for manual use.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Cross-engine baseline JSON exists with at least 30 workloads spanning all op-families listed above, at multiple size tiers.\n- [ ] Each workload has both FNP and NumPy timings with at least 50 samples (or --quick mode for CI).\n- [ ] Ratio direction is fnp/numpy (>1 = FNP slower), confirmed by a unit test.\n- [ ] Environment fingerprint includes BLAS backend detection.\n- [ ] RaptorQ sidecar + scrub_report (status: ok) + decode_proof (recovery_success: true) generated alongside the JSON.\n- [ ] Markdown report is human-readable, grouped by op-family, with summary stats and per-workload band colors.\n- [ ] `scripts/e2e/run_cross_engine_benchmark.sh` runs end-to-end on a fresh checkout (assuming .venv-numpy314 is bootstrapped).\n- [ ] `scripts/e2e/run_cross_engine_benchmark.sh --quick` completes in under 2 minutes for CI.\n- [ ] All 7 unit test categories above pass.\n- [ ] No #[ignore] tests, no todo!(), no panics on malformed manifests (return Result).\n- [ ] Workload YAML manifest is committed and versioned.\n\n## How this serves the over-arching goals\n\nThe README's \"parity debt, not feature cuts\" doctrine assumes we eventually catch up to NumPy on every dimension. Catching up on *behavior* is what 2,894 tests verify. Catching up on *performance* is currently invisible. This bead gives us the first honest snapshot of where we stand and creates the substrate every future optimization bead will measure against. Without it, we can never answer the most important strategic question: \"are we close enough on performance to start the BLAS/Python-FFI/threading phase, or do we still have a 100x gap on basic ops?\"","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"feature","estimated_minutes":480,"created_at":"2026-04-09T00:15:41.124273629Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-10T02:21:30.231379925Z","closed_at":"2026-04-10T02:21:30.231201006Z","close_reason":"Generated cross-engine baseline with 37 workloads. Median ratio 2.1x, range 0.10x-53.6x. All deliverables complete: JSON, markdown report, RaptorQ sidecar/scrub/decode proof, E2E script.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","performance","phase3"]}
